1. Two Sum

Solved
Easy
Topics: Array, Hash Table
Companies: Amazon, Google, Microsoft, Facebook
Hint: Use HashMap to store visited elements

🧾 Problem Statement

Given an array of integers nums and an integer target, return indices of the two numbers such that they add up to target.

Each input has exactly one solution
You cannot use the same element twice
Return answer in any order
🧪 Examples
Example 1:
Input: nums = [2,7,11,15], target = 9  
Output: [0,1]  
Explanation: nums[0] + nums[1] = 2 + 7 = 9
Example 2:
Input: nums = [3,2,4], target = 6  
Output: [1,2]
Example 3:
Input: nums = [3,3], target = 6  
Output: [0,1]
📌 Constraints
2 <= nums.length <= 10^4  
-10^9 <= nums[i] <= 10^9  
-10^9 <= target <= 10^9  
Only one valid answer exists
💡 Approach 1: Brute Force
🧠 Idea:

Check all pairs (i, j) and see if they sum to target.

⏱️ Complexity:
Time: O(n²)
Space: O(1)
💻 Code:
class Solution {
    public int[] twoSum(int[] nums, int target) {
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.length - 1; i++){
            for(int j = i + 1; j < nums.length; j++){
                if(nums[i] + nums[j] == target){
                    return new int[]{i, j};
                }
            }
        }
        return new int[]{-1, -1};
    }
}
🚀 Approach 2: Optimal (HashMap)
🧠 Idea:

Instead of checking all pairs, store visited numbers and check if the required complement exists.

👉 For each number:

complement = target - nums[i]
⏱️ Complexity:
Time: O(n)
Space: O(n)
💻 Code:
import java.util.*;

class Solution {
    public int[] twoSum(int[] nums, int target) {
        HashMap<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

        for(int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++){
            int complement = target - nums[i];

            if(map.containsKey(complement)){
                return new int[]{map.get(complement), i};
            }

            map.put(nums[i], i);
        }

        return new int[]{-1, -1};
    }
}
🔥 Dry Run (Example 2)
nums = [3,2,4], target = 6
i	nums[i]	complement	map before	found?	action
0	3	3	{}	❌	store {3:0}
1	2	4	{3:0}	❌	store {3:0,2:1}
2	4	2	{3:0,2:1}	✅	return [1,2]
⚡ Key Insight

Instead of searching for two numbers,
store one and check if its complement already exists